Electronic music deviant Diwanescu aka s.diwan aka Sabotage Hybrid is one of the harder to pin down acts on the experimental sample landscape. He fuses samples drawn from diverse sources all over the world with hip-hop and jazz compositional ideas - the bustling rhythms of breakbeat, the bent sonic mayhem of ambient and dub are mixed with computers -, sequencers -, keyboards - experiments.
Now residing in the south-spanish village ‘Alcaidesa‘ s.diwan a.ka. Diwanescu started up to produce music in late ‘95 as an adjunct to his respective interests in funk and soul, jazz, hip-hop and experimental underground club styles like house, breakbeat, ambient, dub and downbeat.
In 1997, at the age of 22, his first recording was released. It was called “Befreiung” and was some of the most lovely electronic music work ever recorded and shows hard, dark, experimental style. As the nineties progressed, he recorded and released multiple songs, purely for his own pleasure - also collaborations between him and his friend Dedlef Kedrosch at the happy spacemas festival (turntables/synth project ‘98) and the famous band project “trish” (rhythms of breakbeat, electro-pop-funk, vocals and conventional instruments ‘98) were pushing back s.diwan’s sound clash boundaries.
The following months/years were spent searching and archiving source material for his follow-up, “Project Lift”, which utilized samples from excursions to rolling jungle, cool jazz, galloping basslines with complex trapset orchestration and shrill, screaming horns.
In 2001 s.diwan/diwanescu founded uterus.at digital style grill network-project. Also, tiefparterre.net, a collaboration of DJs, Producers, Graffiti & Tattoo artists was initiated with his assistence.
During following months and years Diwanescu started to play out live and as DJ at various festivals and locations in Austria and Spain.

From guest sets in every corner of America (including Alaska and Hawaii), the Dominican Republic, Europe, Mexico and Russia, to his 6 year residency at New York’s premier underground venue, Sullivan Room, DJ Fame (Amos Damon) has continued to bring the more jackin’ sounds of tech house and electro to crowds of thousands across the world for almost 15 years. His energetic performances showcase some serious technical ability combined with intense cuts, crazy loops, and other turntablist-like tricks to bring a new style and sound to the dance floor. This illuminating stage presence and a rightfully-earned air of confidence sets him apart from so many peers and makes him truly one of the hottest talents on the dance scene.
More About DJ Fame

Fame’s natural progression to the studio gained him worldwide notice in 2006 when his first solo EP “Name It X” was released on one of the most respected UK labels in the industry, Switch’s “Dubsided”. This massive tribal-tech tune earned him the first American producer to join the label, and became a well known tool in the record crates of Richie Hawtin, Danny Howells, Ricardo Villalobos, Switch, Jesse Rose, Jimpster, and countless others.
 
 “Yep I played the track (Name It X) to death, still dropping it  if I'm honest. Reaction has been superb worldwide, I've even had a lot of  people asking me to ID it for them after it featured in my Amsterdam Dance Music set” Danny Howells

Over the next few years, Fame continued to release originals and remixes on labels such as Potty Mouth Music, Loungin’ Records, NOSI music, and others. In 2006, he released a mixed compilation for Sullivan Room showcasing the sound of his residency. It featured mostly artists who were guests at his monthly event, “The Review”.
 
Also that year, Fame began working closely with Gaby Dershin (1/2 of Bedrock  artist Astro&Glyde) on a production project named “Bit Crushers”. The duo immediately started unleashing a slew of tunes on the dance world for labels like Oakenfold’s Perfecto and Kleinenberg’s Little Mountain Records. This gained them major support from top jocks as well as licensing deals with companies like Nokia and the “Tap Tap” iPhone applications. They also found time to drop a 2 disc compilation for the 2nd Sullivan Room series, loaded with tracks from their own discography.

More recently, Fame has been focusing his energy on the newly launched “Rock It Science”, a music label. After 2 years performing guest sets at San Francisco’s infamous RIS events, he officially teamed up with head honcho Eric Sharp to bring the vibe of these amazing nights to you in the form of original musical releases featuring themselves, and other RIS resident DJs and friends. The first few releases are already receiving major support, and the future looks bright for this young, digital imprint!

Ruff & Jam (Respectively Jean-Marie Moens & Luke Mourinet) is a duo of Producers, Remixers, Songwriters and Recording Artists based in Belgium.

In the early days of their collaboration in the mid 90s, they’ve developed a couple of pop acts for the French market with the leading major companies. 

In 2001 the duo decided to wear the remixer’s hat so they picked up the Ruff & Jam Handle and founded their Remix & Production Company : Ruff & Jam Recordings, that same year they’ve started remixing for a couple of British Artists including Sophie Ellis Bextor.

2002 was the emerging year for Ruff & Jam with their official U.S. Radio Mix for Kylie Minogue and Billboard Magazine wrote : ‘With its innovative and catchy remix of Kylie Minogue’s “Love at first sight” (Capitol) riding high on the Billboard dance charts, Belgian production unit Ruff & Jam has made a big step onto the international scene.’

Ruff & Jam got their first Billboard #1 and a Grammy Award nominated Remix within the Best Dance Recording Category.

In 2004 they’ve penned ‘Another Day (Can’t let go)’ & teamed with British Singer Nina Babet (Ozark Henry,Milow…) It became their first single as Ruff & Jam and was released on Sony Music.

Their single hit the Dance Charts at #3 as best new entry and gave them their first Top 20 in the National Charts.

The record received a massive support from radios and an outstanding support among the most respected & Prestigious DJ/Producers including Armand Van Helden, Judge Jules, Tiesto (#1 in his playlist), Ferry Corsten, Joachim Garraud (F*ck me I’m famous),Olav Basoski to name but a few…

They kept on being prolific as remixers and delivered some reworks for The Killers, Robbie Williams, Bob Marley,Marianne Faithful, Sugababes, Amy Winehouse, Frou Frou, Scissors Sisters, Placebo,The Spinto Band,Polyphonic Spree, Mary J Blige, Tiga,we’re from Barcelona, Au Revoir Simone,Mika and more.

As well as collaboration and mix for Composer Extraordinaire Craig Armstrong and official Radio Mixes for Axelle Red, Delavega & Ozark Henry.

Their love and skills for electronic music has given them the opportunity to make some Sound Design work for virtual recreations of legendary synthesizers so they designed factory presets for Arturia’s ARP 2600 V, PROPHET V, JUPITER 8 V and will be in charge of Factory Presets for Arturia’s ORIGIN Hardware Synthesizer.

In 2007, they’ve founded their label Over:Kraft and signed a deal for one of their act on the legendary Southern Fried Records Label (Armand Van Helden, Mighty Dub Katz(Fatboy Slim)…).

2008 is the debut of an exciting partnership with Talpa Music.

HomeSkillet Records is a grassroots record label with a focus on digital distribution. We have an eclectic group of artists under the label and we do whatever we can to help them achieve their goals. Our initial motto was, “Steal Our Music,” as we gave it all away for free. Then a lightbulb went off that we need to make a little bit of money to provide any kind of service at all to our musicians. Now our motto is probably something more like, “Help Feed Nova.”

HomeSkillet Records was founded in 2004 by Nicholas Galanin and George Huff. Both were going to school and living abroad when they began discussing the idea of taking what they had been experiencing in the Summers in Sitka, Alaska, and turning it into something more organized, a record label.

It was never intended to be a record label in a traditional sense, as both Nicholas and George were digitally saavy and the vision was more in line with distributing over internet than printing out CDs and touring.

In the first year Nicholas and George spent a lot of time talking about what they would like to do. Many conversations happened late at night over IM from England to New Zealand. Both having the same fondness for the community which raised them, it was only natural for the label’s home to reside in Sitka. Because of the plans to distribute over the web - the isolation from being in Sitka was looked at as incubation, and a chance for them to hone their skills with fellow HomeSkillet Records artists.

After the first Summer HSR officially had a couple of condenser microphones, a website, and a total of four artists living under the label. Silver Jackson recorded, “Meet You At 8″ for the first time in George’s parents basement and then it was put immediately on the web.  We had one million downloads in the first 72 hours.  And then we retired to a beach somewhere with blazing hot sun and free drinks.  After waking up we found ourselves in the dead of Winter with little to no traction for the label.

HSR has always described itself as a Summertime label - due only to the fact both Nicholas and George, as well as the rest of the HSR crew were always in Sitka in the Summer, and that’s when the most momentum was captured. After the second Summer HSR added three more bluesman to the roster, all while putting out two albums Silver Jacksons “Fools and Thieves,” and “Seal it in a Box,” a compilation of the first four HSR artists.

I am an electronic music producer hailing from Sydney, Australia. You can expect some blend of house or techno to be coming out of my studio always more aligned to the more progressive, melodic and deeper sides of those genres.

--

I grew up on a diet of 80’s euro-pop and 90’s electronic beats, artists like Eurythmics, Chemical Brothers and the Prodigy are really where it all began for me. When I started to get into DJing it was the nuskool breaks movement that really grabbed me. As I immersed myself in the music at that time, I found myself drawn towards the more progressive breaks sound of artists like Beta, Hybrid, Mesmer and Nubreed to name a few. 

This attraction towards the deeper more melodic side is a theme that would continue even as the strictly broken beat sounds of many of my favourite artists, DJ sets and indeed my own productions started to wane and evolve into something more influenced by house or techno with a steady four to the floor rhythm.

Whatever style of music I'm making you can expect lush soundscapes, gritty textures, a good kick & bass drop as well as a cheeky breakbeat from time to time.

Gyorgy Udvardy was born in 1978, Budapest, Hungary. He experienced electronic music in 1993, four years later he started producing, using the name MiraculuM from the very beginning. The inspiration behind his name selection was trance artists and the latin language's dignified sounding. His first official release was in 2004, when he won a remix competition for the official hungarian Loveparade hymn. In this period his music was goa trance, with a little pointing back to the 90's, and the touch of Holland's actual new wave sound. In 2008 he spent a year in Norway, started bedroom djing and listening to more progressiver and deeper music. This had a great impact on his work as a producer, his music became slower, cleaner and leisurely, and it aroused some labels attention. His music was signed to such labels as Balkan Connection, Soundteller, Clinique, Slideways, or Lowbit. One of his tracks called 'Constellation' included in the legendary Masters-Series compilation, mixed by Nick Warren and released on Renaissance. His first artist album called 'Die Quelle Der Seele' released by Stripped Recordings in 2015. In 2014, the biggest online electronic-music shop, Beatport picked his track 'Aftermath' to their official chart where they collected the best ten progressive house tracks from the last ten years. He also started a monthly podcast 'Simple Pleasures', around 2009 where he selects from his actual favourites. Last but not least he established a Proton-sub label with Erich Von Kollar and Greyloop, called Stellar Fountain Records, which grew into the world's top hundred progressive house labels within years.

MiraculuM tracks played by:

Armin Van Buuren, Aly & Fila, Jaytech, Ruben De Ronde, Hernan Cattaneo, D-Nox, Marcus Schössow, John Askew, Nick Warren, Max Graham, Solid Stone, Gai Barone, Airwave, Nicolas Rada, Dmitry Molosh, Mariano Mellino, Emi Galvan, GMJ, John 00 Fleming, Golan Zocher, Mashk, Andromedha, Graziano Raffa, Li-Polymer, Alexey Sonar, Basil O'Glue, Andrea Cassino, Tim Penner.

Peter Paul is a DJ and producer that has been releasing tracks since the 1990s. He has a huge back catalogue under his belt of many singles, and 5 artist albums. He is an ambassador for Spanish electronic music from Andalucia, and has brought his own unique, pioneering take on the vibrant Sevillilian music scene to the world stage. He has crafted a proprietary sound that pushes boundaries, and has been supported by major artists from around the world. Support for his music has come from the likes of Phil Hartnoll (Orbital), James Zabiela, Eric Morillo, The Crystal Method, and many more. 

Peter Paul is also a successful label owner with his imprint N-Mity Sound, and curator of club nights and events in the south of Spain, and the UK. As well as his own critically acclaimed tracks, he has put out a number of slick, forward thinking mixes, including one of a set at Glastonbury Festival that was broadcasted on the Annie Nightingale show on BBC Radio 1. He has played at many other large festivals worldwide, and toured the world playing as far afield as Australia, Russia, Poland, Hungary, UK, and Spain. Awards received by Peter Paul have accumulated over the years, and include ‘Best DJ’, ‘Best Label (N-Mity Sound)’, and ‘Best Producer’.

Resident DJ & Promoter for Uber Birmingham - Vocal Booth Weekender Spain (Resident) 

From a young age Richie Barthez has always immersed himself in quality music. Surrounding himself with the genres of House, Soul, Funk, Disco, Jazz Funk & Hip Hop, his influences have a rich and diverse pedigree between them. Those with a trained ear will pick up on these when experiencing one of his sets today.
Learning his trade in the mid 90’s, Richie started out like many other successful DJ’s before him – in his bedroom on a pair of turntables. During an extremely competitive time and era of the ‘Super DJ’, Richie’s hard teenage work and self promotion through mixtapes lead to a weekly residency at the Medicine Bar in Birmingham. This turned out to be his breakthrough, and in turn lead to regular appearances and residencies over the next few years at the The Que Club, Birmingham Arts Festival, BPM Radio, Wobble, Red Worcester, RSVP Worcester and Bonds.
2003 saw Richie take his skills beyond Birmingham and the UK, with regular appearances in Worcester, Coventry, Birmingham, Nottingham and Spain.
With a proven background behind him, Richie’s diary has snowballed since 2009. After playing numerous House nights in and around Birmingham, he is now resident for the hugely successful monthly night Uber & Days Like This ‘Together’ in central Birmingham, twice monthly resident at the ‘Hole In The Wall’ (Bar Room Bar) in Stratford Upon Avon, and has once again played at the annual ‘Vocal Booth Weekender’ on the South Coast of Spain – an event that’s grown tenfold year on year.
With regular appearances also at the ‘Beat Players’ night in London, plus some global opportunities on the cards for 2012, Richie’s schedule is only set to get a lot more hectic...

There are plenty of bedroom producers out there using the latest and greatest plugins and soft synths to create their music, but what sets Dylan Abbott (aka Miniature Airlines) apart from the rest is his attention to songcraft. Instead of following dancefloor-oriented templates to build his tracks, he draws on his background as a songwriter to make structured pop songs full of melodic development, while borrowing techniques from the worlds of IDM, glitch, and synthpop. Using the obtuse and crash-prone tracker program known as Buzz, he has released a string of EPs in the last few years, followed by his first full-length album, Arrivals & Departures, in 2010. If you catch one of his live performances, expect longer, deconstructed version of his songs, along with new, unreleased material with the same melodic sensibilities.

My name is Budy Mokoginta. I'm a guitar player, songwriter and I work with other artists as a producer, mix engineer or master engineer. I never really planned to do so, it just happened. I begun my project studio as an extension to my own musical ambitions, but soon I started to (co) produce and mix for other artists. They came to me for what they call the 'Moko' sound; I love organic sound and don't like to restrict music by some kind of law on how it should sound. The first artist who's album I mixed therefore revered to my studio as the Mokosound studio and ever since that has been the name. Since then I've worked on a lot of different projects with different styles; Pop, Jazz, Soul, HipHop, D&B, Jungle, World music and specially all kinds of crossover between styles. I had a producer contract with Sony Benelux.

These days I concentrate on independent music, which often means trying to get an organic sound of music made or recorded with computers. My main project is with iET and Russ Elevado, my sonic hero. My work with iET involves production, co-writing, concept development and playing a lot of instruments.

About songwriting and producing
Songdesign and producing is the subscript of my logo. What I mean with that is: helping artists to get the best out of their music. Songdesign and producing is all about making the most out of a song. It concentrates on the question how to get the most intense musical experience of a song using it's full potential. The answer is often simple: though it's been a fashion to try to impress the audience with heavy production techniques and intensive mixing tricks, doing less often benefits the song more.

A good song has all the right ingredients in itself. It needs an understanding performance of an artist who is being the song instead of acting it. The production should enhance it's beauty and energy without taking over, like good make up. And like with make up, sometimes not using it is the most perfect solution.

About mixing and mastering
In simple words: mixing is making the music sound great in the mixing studio, mastering is making sure people don't start to jump at their level control fiddling about with their equalizers every new song or on every other sound system they play the songs.
To me the difference between mixing and mastering is in short: mixing is enhancing the energy of the music so that the sound and energy flow is as good as possible, within the given time and budget, in the place you are mixing. Mastering is translating that mix to translate and sound as good as possible on all different sound systems, from i-pod to P.A. while keeping a constant and similar coherence of level and sound between different the different tracks presented on an album.

Some things I learned the hard way: you don't want to fix a song with the production, you don't want to fix the production in the mix and you don't want to fix the mix in the mastering. Give each part of the process your full devotion and when you're stuck; get a second opinion, get advice, get help. Collaborate. No great music is created alone.

Muzik 4 machines is a live electronic music project from Quebec, Canada. Performing live with hardware synthesizers, using no pre-recorded sound or backing tracks, he creates a plethora of sounds ranging from electro to drum and bass, always with the same minimalist modus operandi; Distorted analog and punchy sampled drums, a few monophonic synths a couple of samplers, lots of effects and constant sonic mangling and tweaking.
	
 
It all began in 1991 with a Portastudio, a guitar and a TR-707 drum machine; early compositions were a mix between early house and grunge music, mixing the 4 on the floor rhythm with loud fuzz guitar. As the technology evolved, so did the Project; recruiting performers and signers and buying, finding or building new gadgets and sound mangling devices. When computer became powerful enough to generate and process sound, a new page of M4M history started.
 
The Music also evolved from simple riffs over a steady beat to more complex and mysterious texture in some works and at the same time exploded into Rave party music in others. They got some good charts apparition online and even sold Cd's worldwide on the then underground mp3.com website that since closed.
 

Back to minimal electro house, Muzik 4 Machines is now producing new material, performing it live, and distributing it via bit torrent, youtube and a multitude of online music stores from around the world (iTunes, Amazon)
